reviewText:
After the 2nd playthrough and Bitterblack Isle
Dragon's Dogma: Dark Arisen is an action-RPG. The game is something between:Gothic II;
Dragon Age: Inquisition (if you play online with AI companions);
Shadow of the Colossus.
Update.Graphics. The cut-scenes, environment and opponents look gorgeous. Textures are a bit blurry, but it's hard to notice during gameplay. Worth mentioning that nights in DD:DA are really dark.
http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=605087994
http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=605567012
Sound. Boss battle themes are beautiful, other compositions are fine (not annoying). VA is good, Grigori's actor is perfect. Pawns shouting advices during fights are fine as long as they don't have high voices.
Controls are customizable, except for few key bindings. Playing with KB+M is comfortable and enjoyable.
Battles at the beginning, end-game dungeon and Bitterblack Isle require tactical thinking, appropriate party and good equipment, attacking head-on might lead to failure.
Interactions with NPC include mostly actions (to give a quest item, to initiate a conversation, to escort safely to a location), dialogue options usually are binary.
One save slot per account is the only downside. It's possible to make more characters with Steam Family Sharing or manually move savefiles (not recommended) with cloud saves disabled and launching the game in offline mode.

Random info:Don't use any walkthrough on the first PT;
Complete side quests before doing the main ones;
Updated. Choose appearance and vocation for the main pawn similar to protagonist's;
You get access to Fast Travel in Gran Soren (take the Eternal Ferrystone from your Item storage);
You can change Arisen's and Main Pawn's classes in Gran Soren;
Character Editor becomes available very late;
Don't put the Princess Outfit on your Pawn.

